===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `cd` baraye tagheer dadan `pooshe` (directory) kari estefade mishavad. Yani, shoma ba in dastoor mitoonid az yek `pooshe` be `pooshe` dige berid. 🚶‍♀️🚶‍♂️

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `cd`       --> 🏠 Bargashtan be `pooshe` asli (home directory).
    🔹 `cd ..`    --> ⬆️ Raftan be `pooshe` baladasti (parent directory).
    🔹 `cd -`     --> ↩️ Raftan be `pooshe` ghabli ke dar an boodid.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ cd Documents

    🔹 Rafdan be `pooshe` "Documents".

    $ cd /home/user/Downloads

    🔹 Raftan be `pooshe` "Downloads" ba address kamil.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ pwd
    /home/user

    $ cd Documents

    $ pwd
    /home/user/Documents

    🔹 Dastoor `pwd` neshon mide ke shoma kojayid. `cd Documents` shoma ra be `pooshe` Documents bord, va `pwd` address jadid ra neshon midahad.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `cd` command is used to change the working directory. It allows you to navigate between different directories. 🚶‍♀️🚶‍♂️

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `cd`       --> 🏠 Return to the home directory.
    🔹 `cd ..`    --> ⬆️ Go to the parent directory.
    🔹 `cd -`     --> ↩️ Go to the previous directory.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ cd Documents

    🔹 Navigate to the "Documents" directory.

    $ cd /home/user/Downloads

    🔹 Navigate to the "Downloads" directory using the absolute path.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ pwd
    /home/user

    $ cd Documents

    $ pwd
    /home/user/Documents

    🔹 The `pwd` command shows your current location. `cd Documents` moves you to the Documents directory, and `pwd` shows the new location.